title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m,n\in \mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> be integers. If <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[m]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n]]></fr:tex> are coprime <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\gcd (m,n)=1]]></fr:tex>, then for all <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a,b\in \mathbb {Z}]]></fr:tex> the system of congruences
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {align*}x&\equiv  a\pmod {n}\\ x&\equiv  b\pmod {m}\end {align*}]]></fr:tex>
has a unique solution modulo <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[mn]]></fr:tex>, i.e., <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x_{k}=x_{0}+kmn\mid  k\in \mathbb {Z}\}]]></fr:tex> is the set of all possible solutions.</fr:p>
 
   
